label.value: baroreceptor detection of arterial stretch

value.value: The series of events by which the change in diameter of an artery is detected and converted to a molecular signal.

label.value: baroreceptor response to decreased systemic arterial blood pressure

value.value: The lowering of the number of nerve impulses from baroreceptors as a result of decreased stretch of an artery that results in an increased in sympathetic nerve impulses to peripheral blood vessels.

label.value: baroreceptor response to increased systemic arterial blood pressure

value.value: The increase in nerve impulses from baroreceptors as a result of increased pressure on an artery that results in an inhibition of sympathetic nerve impulses to peripheral blood vessels.

label.value: artery vasodilation involved in baroreceptor response to increased systemic arterial blood pressure

value.value: An increase in the internal diameter of an artery, triggered by vasomotor suppression, during the chemoreceptor response to decreased blood pressure.

label.value: negative regulation of heart rate involved in baroreceptor response to increased systemic arterial blood pressure

value.value: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of heart contraction as a result of the baroreceptor response to increased blood pressure.

label.value: negative regulation of the force of heart contraction involved in baroreceptor response to increased systemic arterial blood pressure

value.value: Any process that decreases the force with which the cardiac muscles of the heart pump blood through the circulatory system as a result of the baroreceptor response to increased blood pressure.

label.value: vasoconstriction of artery involved in baroreceptor response to lowering of systemic arterial blood pressure

value.value: A process that is triggered by vasomotor excitation and results in a decrease in the diameter of an artery during the baroreceptor response to decreased blood pressure.

label.value: positive regulation of heart rate involved in baroreceptor response to decreased systemic arterial blood pressure

value.value: Any process that activates, maintains or increases the frequency, rate or extent of heart contraction as a result of the baroreceptor response to decreased blood pressure.

label.value: regulation of systemic arterial blood pressure by hormone

value.value: The process in which hormones modulate the force with which blood passes through the circulatory system. A hormone is one of a group of substances formed in very small amounts in one specialized organ or group of cells and carried (sometimes in the bloodstream) to another organ or group of cells, in the same organism, upon which they have a specific regulatory action.

label.value: regulation of systemic arterial blood pressure by circulatory renin-angiotensin

value.value: The process in which angiotensinogen metabolites in the bloodstream modulate the force with which blood passes through the circulatory system. The process begins when renin is released and cleaves angiotensinogen.

label.value: regulation of systemic arterial blood pressure by vasopressin

value.value: The regulation of blood pressure mediated by the signaling molecule vasopressin. Vasopressin is produced in the hypothalamus, and affects vasoconstriction, and renal water transport.

label.value: regulation of systemic arterial blood pressure by norepinephrine-epinephrine

value.value: The process in which the secretion of norepinephrine or epinephrine into the bloodstream modulates the force with which blood passes through the circulatory system.

label.value: norepinephrine-epinephrine vasoconstriction involved in regulation of systemic arterial blood pressure

value.value: A process that results in a decrease in the diameter of an artery during the norepinephrine-epinephrine response to decreased blood pressure.

label.value: norepinephrine-epinephrine catabolic process in blood stream

value.value: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of norepinephrine or epinephrine in the bloodstream.

label.value: positive regulation of heart rate by epinephrine-norepinephrine

value.value: The process in which the presence of epinephrine or norepinephrine in the bloodstream activates, maintains or increases the rate of heart contraction.

label.value: positive regulation of the force of heart contraction by epinephrine-norepinephrine

value.value: Any process that increases the force with which the cardiac muscles of the heart pump blood through the circulatory system as a result of the presence of epinephrine or norepinephrine in the bloodstream or released from the nerve endings.

label.value: angiotensin-mediated vasoconstriction involved in regulation of systemic arterial blood pressure

value.value: The decrease in blood vessel diameter as a result of the release of angiotensin into the blood stream.

label.value: renal response to blood flow involved in circulatory renin-angiotensin regulation of systemic arterial blood pressure

value.value: The physiological response of the kidneys to a decrease in blood flow.

label.value: detection of renal blood flow

value.value: The process in which the juxtaglomerular cells of the kidneys receive information about the amount of blood flowing through the arterioles and converts the information to a molecular signal.

label.value: renin secretion into blood stream

value.value: The regulated release of renin into the blood stream by juxtoglomerular cells.

label.value: regulation of angiotensin levels in blood

value.value: The process that modulates the level of any of the various angiotensinogen proteolytic products in the blood. This occurs by the proteolytic cleavage of angiotensinogen, and its proteolytic products, to create a variety of active peptide hormones, such as angiotensin I and angiotensin II, as well as through the removal of these peptides from the circulation.

label.value: angiotensin maturation

value.value: The process leading to the attainment of the full functional capacity of angiotensin by conversion of angiotensinogen into mature angiotensin in the blood.

label.value: secretion of vasopressin involved in fast regulation of systemic arterial blood pressure

value.value: The regulated release of the hormone vasopressin into the blood stream by the hypothalamus and pituitary gland contributing to fast regulation of blood pressure.

label.value: vasoconstriction by vasopressin involved in systemic arterial blood pressure control

value.value: The decrease in blood vessel diameter as a result of the release of vasopressin into the blood stream.

label.value: detection of hypoxic conditions in blood by chemoreceptor signaling

value.value: The process in which information about a lack of oxygen are received and are converted to a molecular signal by chemoreceptors in the carotid bodies and the aortic bodies.

label.value: excitation of vasomotor center by chemoreceptor signaling

value.value: The process in which the molecular signal from the carotid and aortic bodies is relayed to the vasomotor center, causing it to signal an increase arterial pressure.

label.value: morphogenesis of an epithelium

value.value: The process in which the anatomical structures of epithelia are generated and organized. An epithelium consists of closely packed cells arranged in one or more layers, that covers the outer surfaces of the body or lines any internal cavity or tube.

label.value: excitation of vasomotor center by baroreceptor signaling

value.value: The process in which the molecular signal from the arterial baroreceptors is relayed to the vasomotor center causing it to signal increase arterial pressure.

label.value: morphogenesis of an epithelial sheet

value.value: The process in which the anatomical structures of an epithelial sheet are generated and organized. An epithelial sheet is a flat surface consisting of closely packed epithelial cells.

label.value: vasoconstriction of artery involved in chemoreceptor response to lowering of systemic arterial blood pressure

value.value: A process that is triggered by vasomotor excitation and results in a decrease in the diameter of an artery during the chemoreceptor response to decreased blood pressure.

label.value: detection of carbon dioxide by vasomotor center

value.value: The process by a carbon dioxide stimulus is received and converted to a molecular signal by the vasomotor center of the central nervous system.

label.value: vasoconstriction of artery involved in ischemic response to lowering of systemic arterial blood pressure

value.value: The vasoconstriction that is triggered by vasomotor excitation resulting from the detection of high carbon dioxide levels in the vasomotor center of the central nervous system.

label.value: regulation of systemic arterial blood pressure by atrial baroreceptor feedback

value.value: A process that controls blood pressure by sensing the amount of stretch occurring in the atria.

label.value: regulation of blood volume by renin-angiotensin

value.value: The process in which the renin-angiotensin system controls the rate of fluid intake and output into the blood.

label.value: regulation of blood volume by renal aldosterone

value.value: The process in which the hormone aldosterone decreases the rate of diuresis and natriuresis resulting in increased blood volume.

label.value: renin-angiotensin regulation of aldosterone production

value.value: The process in which an increase in active angiotensin stimulates the adrenal cortices to secrete aldosterone.

label.value: regulation of renal output by angiotensin

value.value: The process in which angiotensin directly modulates the rate of urine output by the kidney.

label.value: protease binding

value.value: Binding to a protease or a peptidase.

label.value: response to dietary excess

value.value: The physiological process in which dietary excess is sensed by the central nervous system, resulting in a reduction in food intake and increased energy expenditure.

label.value: detection of dietary excess

value.value: The neurological process in which the brain senses excessive caloric intake.

label.value: reduction of food intake in response to dietary excess

value.value: An eating behavior process whereby detection of a dietary excess results in a decrease in intake of nutrients.

label.value: diet induced thermogenesis

value.value: The process that results in increased metabolic rate in tissues of an organism. It is triggered by the detection of dietary excess. This process is achieved via signaling in the sympathetic nervous system.

label.value: norepinephrine-epinephrine-mediated vasodilation involved in regulation of systemic arterial blood pressure

value.value: A process that results in an increase in the diameter of an artery during the norepinephrine-epinephrine response to blood pressure change.

label.value: regulation of the force of heart contraction

value.value: Any process that modulates the extent of heart contraction, changing the force with which blood is propelled.

label.value: regulation of heart rate

value.value: Any process that modulates the frequency or rate of heart contraction.

label.value: regulation of sodium ion transport

value.value: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of the directed movement of sodium ions (Na+) into, out of or within a cell, or between cells, by means of some agent such as a transporter or pore.

label.value: desensitization of G protein-coupled receptor signaling pathway

value.value: The process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of G protein-coupled receptor signaling pathway after prolonged stimulation with an agonist of the pathway.

label.value: inhibitory G protein-coupled receptor phosphorylation

value.value: The process that inhibits the signaling function of a G protein-coupled receptor by addition of a phosphate group to its third intracellular loop consensus site.

label.value: G protein-coupled receptor internalization

value.value: The process that results in the uptake of a G protein-coupled receptor into an endocytic vesicle.

label.value: angiotensin-mediated vasodilation involved in regulation of systemic arterial blood pressure

value.value: The process that increases the diameter of a blood vessel via the renin-angiotensin system.
